04587nam a22005655i 9780822388302DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20062006ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223883027 a10.1515/97808223883022doi  a(DE-B1597)553732  a(OCoLC)1224278669  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aSD566.N6bK67 2006 7aNAT0380002bisacsh1 aKosek, Jake, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUnderstories :bThe Political Life of Forests in Northern New Mexico /cJake Kosek. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (408 p.) :b36 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aA John Hope Franklin Center Book00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tONE. The Cultural Politics of Memory and Longing -- tTWO. Sovereign Natures -- tTHREE. Passionate Attachments and the Nature of Belonging -- tFOUR. Racial Degradation and Environmental Anxieties -- tFIVE. ''Smokey Bear Is a White Racist Pig'' -- tSIX. Nuclear Natures: In the Shadows of the City on the Hill -- tConclusion: On Piñon and Politics -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThrough lively, engaging narrative, Understories demonstrates how volatile politics of race, class, and nation animate the notoriously violent struggles over forests in the southwestern United States. Rather than reproduce traditional understandings of nature and environment, Jake Kosek shifts the focus toward material and symbolic "natures," seemingly unchangeable essences central to formations of race, class, and nation that are being remade not just through conflicts over resources but also through everyday practices by Chicano activists, white environmentalists, and state officials as well as nuclear scientists, heroin addicts, and health workers. Drawing on two years of ethnographic fieldwork and extensive archival research, he shows how these contentious natures are integral both to environmental politics and the formation of racialized citizens, politicized landscapes, and modern regimes of rule.Kosek traces the histories of forest extraction and labor exploitation in northern New Mexico, where Hispano residents have forged passionate attachments to place. He describes how their sentiments of dispossession emerged through land tenure systems and federal management programs that remade forest landscapes as exclusionary sites of national and racial purity. Fusing fine-grained ethnography with insights gleaned from cultural studies and science studies, Kosek shows how the nationally beloved Smokey the Bear became a symbol of white racist colonialism for many Hispanos in the region, while Los Alamos National Laboratory, at once revered and reviled, remade regional ecologies and economies. Understories offers an innovative vision of environmental politics, one that challenges scholars as well as activists to radically rework their understandings of relations between nature, justice, and identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aForest ecologyzNew MexicozEspanola Region. 0aForest managementzNew MexicozEspanola Region. 0aForest policyzNew MexicozEspanola Region. 0aForestry and communityzNew MexicozEspanola Region. 7aNATURE / Natural Resources.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822388302zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822388302423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822388302.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  